hands_on_practices.problem:
A common simplified model for a wingtip trailing vortex is a Rankine vortex combined with an axial flow component. This composite vortex structure is situated in an incompressible Newtonian fluid of constant dynamic viscosity $\mu$. In a cylindrical coordinate system $(r, \theta, z)$ aligned with the vortex axis, the velocity field $\vec{v} = v_\theta(r) \hat{e}_\theta + v_z(r) \hat{e}_z$ is described as follows.

The tangential velocity component, $v_\theta(r)$, adheres to the Rankine vortex model with circulation $\Gamma$ and core radius $a$:
$$
v_\theta(r) = \begin{cases}
\frac{\Gamma r}{2\pi a^2} & \text{for } r \le a \quad \text{(vortex core)} \\
\frac{\Gamma}{2\pi r} & \text{for } r > a \quad \text{(outer region)}
\end{cases}
$$

The axial velocity component, $v_z(r)$, represents an "axial jet" that is non-zero only within the vortex core. It is given by a parabolic profile:
$$
v_z(r) = \begin{cases}
U_{max}\left(1 - \frac{r^2}{a^2}\right) & \text{for } r \le a \quad \text{(vortex core)} \\
0 & \text{for } r > a \quad \text{(outer region)}
\end{cases}
$$
where $U_{max}$ is the maximum axial velocity at the center of the vortex ($r=0$).

The rate of viscous energy dissipation per unit volume, $\Phi$, for an incompressible Newtonian fluid is given by $\Phi = 2\mu S_{ij}S_{ij}$, where $S_{ij}$ is the rate-of-strain tensor. In cylindrical coordinates for a velocity field of the form $\vec{v}(r, \theta, z) = v_r \hat{e}_r + v_\theta \hat{e}_\theta + v_z \hat{e}_z$, this is expressed as:
$$
\Phi = \mu \left\{ 2\left[ \left(\frac{\partial v_r}{\partial r}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial v_\theta}{\partial \theta} + \frac{v_r}{r}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{\partial v_z}{\partial z}\right)^2 \right] + \left(\frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial v_r}{\partial \theta} + r\frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left(\frac{v_\theta}{r}\right)\right)^2 + \left(\frac{\partial v_r}{\partial z} + \frac{\partial v_z}{\partial r}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{\partial v_\theta}{\partial z} + \frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial v_z}{\partial \theta}\right)^2 \right\}
$$

Derive an expression for the total rate of viscous energy dissipation per unit length, $D_{core}$, contained strictly within the core of this vortex (i.e., for $r \le a$).
